Items.Title: RC-198 - Beer Jar
Items.AdditionalInfo: This jar was most likely used for the drinking of beer. Its most notable feature is its rounded bottom. This did not allow the consumer to set it down on the floor or table. As a result the consumer would probably end up drinking more liquid, and create a better profit for the supplier of the liquid.

Items.Title: RC-358 - Pharaoh Head Fragment
Items.AdditionalInfo: Tutankhamun, perhaps the most famous pharaoh of ancient Egypt, is the king depicted in this fragment of a sculpture. It was long believed that Tutankhamun left little behind him save his tomb, but it now appears that much of his art was usurped by later kings - King Horemheb in particular.

Items.Title: RC-367 - Apis Bull Head Mummy
Items.AdditionalInfo: In the Memphite creation myth the god Ptah was believed to have created the universe and the deities via the thoughts in his heart and by speaking words. He was the patron god of craftsmen and artisans. The Apis bull was regarded as the spokesman of Ptah and his glorious soul. The Apis bull was given titles like those of a pharaoh, and when the bull died, like a pharaoh, he was given a burial worthy of a living deity on earth.

Items.AdditionalInfo: This funerary boat was made to fulfill a pilgrimage in the Afterlife; the need to visit Abydos, the holy place in Egypt where the god Osiris was believed to have been entombed. This boat includes the coffin of the deceased and even the mourning wife, acting out the role of Isis.

Items.Title: RC-687 - Granary Model
Items.AdditionalInfo: Granaries were required in the Afterlife, to assure an endless supply of grain, and models such as this one filled the need.  It even includes a scribe to record the amount of grain placed in the granary, to ensure that no theft occurred.

Items.Title: RC-708 - Stars & Planets Tablet
Items.AdditionalInfo: This tablet listing the names of the stars and planets dates from 2750 BCE and is made of unbaked clay. This tablet is a lexicon, a simple listing of names of all known stars and planets in Mesopotamia around the year 2750 BCE. It was probably written by a young school student who was learning to memorize this list.

Items.AdditionalInfo: This statue is one of only seven statues of Cleopatra to survive from the ancient world. It shows archaizing in the body form and is meant to remind the viewer of the many generations that Cleopatra's family ruled Egypt. This is a political statement in the form of art.

Items.Title: RC-1585 - Early Dynastic Coffin
Items.AdditionalInfo: The coffins of the Early Dynastic Period were intended for a contracted burial with the body in a fetal position. This coffin was excavated at Kafr Tarkhan near the Faiyum by Sir W.M.F. Petrie.

The images were later moved to Karnak, and this is presumed to be one of them. In her right hand Sekhmet holds an ankh; in the left, a lotus.

The standard made coffins in ancient Egypt were made for people of average size. When they slammed the coffin closed, it not only broke the mask of the face, but also the nose underneath the mask.

Items.Title: RC-1724 - Swimming Cattle Relief

This peiod was a time of political collapse in Egypt as a result of the low inundation of the Nile caused by a drought in central Africa. In spite of that, this piece is of fine workmanship demonstrating that the tomb owner had access to the finest artists who were still available.

RC-1777 - Usermontu's Coffin
Items.AdditionalInfo: Usermontu, the priest of Montu, Lord of Thebes, was a son of Besenmut and a close relative of Ta'awa-Sherit (RC 2071 - the coffin next to his), possibly a cousin. Coincidentally, these coffins made their way to the Rosicrucian Egyptian Museum, and the family is now at least partially reunited. This family was very powerful during the turmoil of the Saite Period.

Items.Title: RC-1779 - Mummy (from Usermontu's Coffin)
Items.AdditionalInfo: This male mummy has long been an enigma. He does not display the traditional style of mummification of the time period of the coffin in which he arrived. A piece of adhered linen from his wrist dates to 400 BCE, but the style of mummification leans toward the Ramesside Period, or perhaps slightly later. Crossed arms on a mummy of that time period tells us he could well be royalty.

Items.Title: RC-1962 - Cross
Items.AdditionalInfo:
Stylized human figure on front and Coptic cross on back.

Priests of the Coptic Church carry hand-held crosses such as this even today. The image on the front could be a saint or perhaps the Virgin, clutching her heart in remembrance of the Biblical phrase "...and a sword shall pierce your heart." The reverse side of this small cross is a stylized Coptic cross, although the hanle bears the divine beard design, a hold-over from a more ancient time.

RC-2070 - Akhnaton Prayer Relief Fragment
Items.AdditionalInfo: This polychrome fragment of a column depicts Akhnaton offering incense to his sole god, the Aton, and being blessed by the hieroglyph for life in return. The cartouches indicate that this column dates to early in Akhnaton's reign, no later than year nine.

Items.Title: RC-2071 - Ta'awa Coffin
Items.AdditionalInfo: The Lady of the House Ta'awa was from a very prominent family of the Saite Period. Her father, Hori, was priest of Montu, Lord of Thebes, and relative of Besenmut. Ta'awa's own titles, Lady of the House and Noble Lady, tell us little of her own activities, but her brother, Ankh-Hor, was also a priest of Montu.

Items.Title: RC-2080 - Scribe's Canopic Jar
Items.AdditionalInfo: This canopic jar dates from the Nineteenth Dynasty and is made of calcite pigment and gilt. It belonged to a scribe in the treasury of ancient Egypt. A canopic jar was intended for the ritual placement of the mummified organs of the deceased individual.  Kneeling on the front of this canopic jar you can see the canopic jar's owner.

Items.Title: RC-2081 - Incense Burner
Items.AdditionalInfo: This wand was used to offer incense for censing the deity. An incense bead was held in the cartouche-shaped cup before the kneeling king, and a metal cup (now missing) rested on the hand and held charcoal. The offering priest or king picked up the incense with tweezers and dropped it into the burning charcoal, resulting in a puff of smoke.

Items.Title: RC-2084 - Babylonian Spirit House
Items.AdditionalInfo: This Babylonian spirit house dates from 2600 BCE and is made of fired ceramic. The people of Babylon believed that the spirits of their ancestors needed a place to return to to be close to their family. These houses were made as those spirit homes. This model was made in Babylon, just outside of the modern city of Bagdad.

Items.Title: RC-2085 - Hathor Aegis
Items.AdditionalInfo: Wearing horned solar disc and jewelled collar.

Items.Title: RC-2089 - Shabti of Men
Items.AdditionalInfo: Men was the father of the sculptor Thutmose, perhaps the most famous sculptor in all of Egyptian history. Men was probably the chief sculptor who worked on the statue of Sekhmet in the previous gallery, as that was made for Amenhotep III, the king under whose reign he primarily worked.
